The original erroneous code fails because the variable lacks an initial value before printing. You must assign a value to the variable before using it in the print statement. Here is the corrected main class that initializes the string properly.

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello world";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

The next class assigns a new value to the same variable name within its own scope. This demonstrates how to reassign a string variable to hold different data.

```java
public class AssignValue {
    public static void assign(String variable) {
        variable = "New content";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

The following class concatenates the variable with another string to create a longer text output. This shows how to join two separate strings together using the plus operator.

```java
public class Concatenate {
    public static String combine(String variable) {
        String suffix = " and goodbye";
        return variable + suffix;
    }
}
```

The final class compares the variable against another string and returns a boolean result indicating if they match. This illustrates how to check for equality between two string values.

```java
public class Compare {
    public static boolean check(String variable) {
        String target = "Hello world";
        return variable.equals(target);
    }
}
```
